.TH SNOBOL4RANDOM 1 "4 Jan 2012" "SNOBOL"
.SH NAME
snobol4random \- SNOBOL4 random number functions

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "-INCLUDE 'random.sno'"
.LP
.B "NUMBER = RANDOM()"
.LP
.B SRANDOM(NUMBER)
.LP
.B SRANDOMDEV()

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The
.BR RANDOM()
function uses a non-linear additive feedback random number generator
employing a default table of size 31 long integers to return
successive pseudo-random numbers in the range from 0 to (2**31)-1.
The period of this random number generator is very large,
approximately 16*((2**31)-1).

.PP
The
.B SRANDOM()
function sets its
.B INTEGER
argument seed as the seed for a new sequence of pseudo-random numbers
to be returned by
.BR RANDOM() .
These sequences
are repeatable by calling
.B SRANDOM()
with the same seed value.
.B RANDOM()
will by default produce a sequence of numbers that can be duplicated
by calling
.B SRANDOM()
with 1 as the seed.
.PP
The
.B SRANDOMDEV()
routine initializes a state array using the
.BR random (4)
random number device (if available) which returns good random numbers,
suitable for cryptographic use.  Note that this particular seeding
procedure can generate states which are impossible to reproduce by
calling
.B SRANDOM()
with any value, since the succeeding terms in the state buffer are no
longer derived from the LC algorithm applied to a fixed seed.  Data
from the
.BR random (4)
device may be precious, and repeated calls to
.B SRANDOMDEV()
should be avoided.
When the 
.BR random (4)
device is not available, a 32-bit seed will be generated using
time, process id, and an element of the process stack.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR snobol4 "(1), " random "(3), " random (4)
.SH AUTHOR
Philip L. Budne
